<br>
I tell you all of this so in case you do not believe what I am about to say, you can come find me and see for yourself that I am honorable and trustworthy in my statements.<br>
<br>
You shall never find a person more dedicated to the mage class than I am. Before I got EQ I did some research on what class I wanted to be. After a while I decided that whatever class it was, I wanted it to be a pet class, leaving it down to 2 real choices, necros, and magicians. I'd already decided at that point I wanted to be an Erudite. I finally decided on magicians due to the multiple pet abilities, and the great dmg spells, and the ability to be totally self reliant. Since that time that I first created Morpherios, I have not once switched to another character. I've spent all of a total of 10 minutes playing other characters. When asked why I never tried a new class, I'd simply return the question and said &quot;Why bother? I've already found everything I need right here.&quot; and then promptly blew something up to proove it. <br>
<br>
The magician is not without it's flaws. One of them being, if that pet dies, you either zone, gate, or run. Unless that mob is on it's last legs, you don't have much of a chance. Some of our summon items are also rather lame. However I've gotten use out of a lot of the things, such as the staves, on corpse retreivals. When you  have lowered mana, It helps to have a nice 10 dmg weapon there to help. Now, the thing is, in order for something to really kill you, it HAS to kill that pet. Unless you're trained or you get more than 2 high blue mobs on you at a time, you're not gonna die if you keep your wits about you.<br>
<br>
FACT: We EASILY have the best pets in the game, and if used properly they will serve to be a better personal tank than any warrior, ranger, paladin, or shadowknight you'll ever group with.<br>
<br>
FACT: Out of any class in this game, we are easily the most self reliant. You buy a good stock of, say, 120 reagents for pets and maybe the phantom shield spells, and you're set for a LONG time of battle in the field. I've gone a month already (real life month, playing 5 hours a day at least) without leaving a dungeon. I never had to leave, weight reduction bags to keep weight low, food/water/bandages/coldstones/pet weapons. Everything I need right inside the spell book.<br>
<br>
FACT: Magicians have a versatility unmatched by any class. Necros are great soloers. Druids are too. But when was the last time you saw them soloing stuff in a dungeon reliably, or a high risk area that was confined. We nearly always solo stuff toe to toe, we can't fear, we can't kite (with the exception of the Jboots people) we can't stun or root (not counting pets, but even when they do, they're going toe to toe with a mob) we can't snare, we can't blind. What do we do? We send our BEASTS of pets into that mob head on. And we blow the sh*t out of it. Our pets' automatic abilities enable them to let us play like that, to do the work quick. I've already been fighting in guk,and ended up with 3 mobs, all about mid blue. I buffed, armed, and flame shielded myself and pet. Sent my pet into the 3 of them. 1 of them was able to get away, and attacked me head on, my pet managed to hold the other 2. I was thinking &quot;oh crap, gate time.&quot; But just before I began to cast, a wonderous thing happened, and I swear to you this is true. My pet, rooted one of the ones he was on, rooted the OTHER one he was on, ran up to me, and rooted the LAST one so I could back off, then he taunted it off me. Together the 2 of us killed it very fast. Then he moved on to the next one. He went after the one closest to us, but the one in back broke root. He casted root on it AGAIN and held it in place, and me and him went and killed the one in front. By this time I was low on mana, but being the earth beast that he was, I threw a heal on him, and he went ahead and solo'd the last one the rest of the way down. True story, not one part is exagerated. And if you need to know where this happened, Lower Guk, take the left hand slippery ramp from the dead side zone, walk down the ramp, down the long hallway, into the circular room where 3 spawn. anyone who's been down there knows that room. <br>
<br>
Another tactic too many people over look, and the one the mages do best, /pet get lost. To those of you unfamiliar, this is used to make your pet die immediately. But it holds a very very rewarding purpose. Let me set up the scenario for you. You're fighting a hill giant. The giant is under half, but you're pet is almost dead, you still have mana to spare but not enough time to blast the HG before the pet dies, what do you do? Type /pet get lost       but do NOT hit enter. Instead, get within pet command range (usually about the same range as a /say would reach) and start to cast a new pet. Once the casting is JUSTabout done, like the last quarter of the last casting bubble, hit enter. Pet suicides, new pet comes out INSTANTLY. Send that bad boy on the HG and now you have the tank you need to finish your fight, no fuss, no muss. Works very very well if used in the right situations. <br>
<br>
That's all well and good, we can solo well. How about groups?<br>
<br>
Just after the patch went live for mage pets to weild weapons, a 50th mage summoned a pet, gave it weapons, burned it out, and flame shielded it. His pet solo'd a bok in lower guk. Think of how useful that would be in a group, especially without an enchanter. Pull to many? Put the pet on one or 2. He'll hold em just fine. Also, at level 39 the highest pet you make can do 40 dmg per shot. Now when he does that 3 times, sometimes 4 a round. Plus if you're using water or fire, he nukes, or if you're using air he stuns, or if earth he roots. That's one hell of an upfront man. And that's just the pet. We can still nuke hard, sure maybe wizards out dmg us with spells alone, but what happens when they go OOM. They sit. What happens when we go OOM? We sit, while our up front man bashes the HELL out of that mob. Ok, how about our dmg shields, best in the game. You got 2 tanks, throw a dmg shield on each of them when the fight gets hairy. If there's more than 2 mobs, that shield's gonna do over 200 dmg in less than 15 seconds. Not bad considering it takes all of, what, 3 seconds to cast, uses little mana, and you just let it work it's magic while you cast yourself. It's like a dot almost. The mob literally beats itself to death while hitting the tank. So you say &quot;well ok but necros can do real DOTs&quot; sure but this one lasts longer than a DOT, and can potentially do more dmg if the fight lasts long enough. Let us not forget coldstones, people love that ultravision. How about bandages for your monks and tanks when there's an absence of a healer? Or food and water to stave off that trip for a group member needing to go to a town to buy while the rest of the group slows down it's progress. Weapons for pets instantly. Malise series to debuff the mobs resists on everything we need, not just magic, but magic cold fire poison. And if you have an enchanter, the tashan series, double your pleasure double your fun, with a red mob that can't resist worth a damn!<br>
<br>
Anyone who's complaining about being a mage should have their head examined. We have power to spare, and a style unique to us. You can fight in a group for 3 hours, and on a whim just decide to go solo somewhere else, and have the power to do that easily. The only people who will turn you away from a group are those who haven't had a good mage in their group yet, be persistant to get them to let you in, and show them what we can do, it'll make life easier for the next mage that comes along needing a group from the same people. So fellow magi, rejoice, no we do not &quot;suck&quot; nor are we poor soloers, or groupers. We are strong. We have all the skills we need rolled into our spell book. Now if you'll all excuse me, I have some hill giants to solo. Let the good times roll!<br>
<br>
~Morpherios Pendraggon<br>
~Level 41 Erudite Magician on Innoruuk<br>
